  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Dialogue is speech between characters in a narrative. In fiction, dialogue does multiple jobs simultaneously: it reveals character, advances plot, conveys information, establishes relationships, and creates rhythm on the page. Dialogue that does only one of these — especially only conveying information — tends to feel artificial.\nGood dialogue is not realistic speech transcribed. Real conversation is full of filler, repetition, false starts, and mutual interruption. Fiction dialogue is compressed — it sounds natural but is shaped to carry meaning. The craft lies in creating the illusion of natural speech while making every line do narrative work.\n",
